The US Securities and Exchange Commission has a rule that, if you work in t=
he financial industry, you are only allowed to communicate=C2=A0about work =
with your colleagues and customers using systems =E2=80=94=C2=A0like your f=
irm email account or=C2=A0Bloomberg messaging =E2=80=94 that your firm can =
archive and review. You are not allowed to use WhatsApp or Signal or iMessa=
ge or text messaging from your personal phone. Financial industry employees=
 have to =E2=80=9Cconduct their communications about business matters withi=
n only official channels, and they must maintain and preserve those communi=
cations,=E2=80=9D as SEC Chair Gary Gensler put it last year, when he fined=
 15=C2=A0banks a total of $1.1 billion for using WhatsApp.
This is a weird rule that the SEC has. For one thing, it is obviously not t=
he rule. Gensler=C2=A0cannot possibly have meant=C2=A0that investment banke=
rs and traders are only allowed to communicate about business using corpora=
te email and Bloomberg messages and recorded phone lines; he is=C2=A0surely=
=C2=A0aware that sometimes a banker will turn to the colleague sitting next=
 to her and say, aloud, =E2=80=9Chey did you finish that pitch deck yet,=E2=
=80=9D and that she will sometimes fly out to meet with a client in a confe=
rence room (or on a golf course) and talk business face to face. Plenty of =
business communication still occurs informally, in person, and it can=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0be preserved until you get every employee into augmented reality =
goggles that record everything.
For another thing, this rule =E2=80=94=C2=A0that you have to do business co=
mmunications only on official channels =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a somewhat new int=
erpretation of the SEC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0actual written rules=C2=A0say. When a=
ll those banks got in trouble last year, they got in trouble for violating =
SEC Rule 17-4(b)(4), which requires broker-dealers to =E2=80=9Cpreserve for=
 a period of not less than three years =E2=80=A6=C2=A0originals of all comm=
unications received and copies of all communications sent (and any approval=
s thereof) by the member, broker or dealer (including inter-office memorand=
a and communications) relating to its business as such.=E2=80=9D I have  po=
inted out before that this rule was written in 1948, when =E2=80=9Cinter-of=
fice memoranda=E2=80=9D were a thing, and when it made sense to talk about =
keeping =E2=80=9Coriginals=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccopies=E2=80=9D of communi=
cations because they were written on typewriters with carbon paper.
This record-keeping requirement was originally meant to apply to fairly=C2=
=A0formal=C2=A0written communications, because it was written=C2=A0back whe=
n written communications were necessarily formal. But now that everyone tex=
ts all the time, the requirement has become=C2=A0vastly broader:=C2=A0Every=
thing that would have been an informal face-to-face chat in 1948 is a text =
message now, and so is swept up in the SEC=E2=80=99s interpretation of its =
rule. It doesn=E2=80=99t seem like quite what the rule meant.
But you can see why the SEC loves its current rule, Gensler=E2=80=99s rule,=
 the one about all communications being on preserved official channels. The=
re are two reasons:
=09This rule is really good for regulation and enforcement. If all business=
 communications have to occur on official channels and be preserved, then t=
he SEC will have an easy time investigating misbehavior: If it has any susp=
icions about anything, it can call a firm and say =E2=80=9Cgive me all the=
=C2=A0messages that Employee X sent about Topic Y last year,=E2=80=9D and t=
he firm will run a search and hand over the messages. It can call=C2=A0ever=
y=C2=A0firm and ask them that. The firms themselves will do it voluntarily:=
 Their compliance people will constantly run searches on their internal mes=
sages, looking for keywords like =E2=80=9Cfraud=E2=80=9D or whatever, and t=
hen hand anything bad over to the SEC. There are not a lot of areas where e=
very crime is meticulously documented in written electronic messages that a=
re preserved and handed over to regulators. Obviously the coverage is not p=
erfect, and there will still be golf courses and in-person meetings, but I =
suppose in the long run technology (goggles, etc.)=C2=A0might stamp those o=
ut too and the SEC will achieve a perfect panopticon.=09This rule is=C2=A0n=
ew, so it is=C2=A0lucrative. Financial firms and their employees=C2=A0reall=
y did not know=C2=A0about the SEC rule that nobody could use WhatsApp to me=
ssage their colleagues, because, again, that=E2=80=99s a somewhat=C2=A0nove=
l interpretation of the actual rules. And so when the SEC decided, in about=
=C2=A02021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0when everyone was working from home due to Covid =
and sending lots of text messages =E2=80=94 that texting about work was ill=
egal, every single bank was doing illegal things. And so the SEC could just=
 kind of go down the line and extract a $125 million fine from each of them=
. It didn=E2=80=99t have to prove any=C2=A0bad=C2=A0behavior: It got sample=
s of the bankers=E2=80=99=C2=A0text and WhatsApp messages and, as far as I =
can tell, never found a single text message relating to any sort of miscond=
uct. It just had to prove that there were text messages about business and,=
 boom, $125 million. =E2=80=9CIt is not literally the case that the US Secu=
rities and Exchange Commission is a for-profit business whose goal is to ma=
ximize its revenue,=E2=80=9D  I once wrote, about this business, but, man. =
This is a profitable business.

The SEC extracted all of those fines through settlements with the banks. I =
suppose the banks could say =E2=80=9Cno, see you in court,=E2=80=9D but I d=
on=E2=80=99t think any have. The SEC=E2=80=99s interpretation of the rule i=
s aggressive, but it=E2=80=99s logical, and it is pretty risky for the bank=
s to fight the SEC on this.
Anyway this rule is so good that, after fining the banks $125 million each =
for violating it, the SEC has moved on to other financial firms. It has lon=
g  been reported that hedge funds, private equity firms and other investmen=
t managers  are next: There are a lot of them, they have deep pockets, sure=
ly they=E2=80=99ve sent some text messages. It would be good, for the SEC, =
to extract money out of them, and it would be good to=C2=A0apply=C2=A0Gensl=
er=E2=80=99s rule to them going forward, so that if they do any crimes in t=
he future they will have meticulous records of those crimes to hand over to=
 the SEC.
There is a bit of a problem with moving on to investment managers, which is=
 that Rule 17-4(b)(4) =E2=80=94=C2=A0the rule that=C2=A0requires broker-dea=
lers to preserve their communications, and that the SEC uses as the basis f=
or its =E2=80=9Conly official channels=E2=80=9D rule =E2=80=94=C2=A0does no=
t apply to investment managers. Investment managers=C2=A0do=C2=A0have a com=
munications-preservation rule, Rule 204-2(a)(7), but it is narrower, coveri=
ng external communications about specific topics (investment recommendation=
s and advice, trade orders, etc.), not the manager=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cbusin=
ess as such.=E2=80=9D In January a bunch of asset-management=C2=A0trade ass=
ociations sent a letter to the SEC arguing =E2=80=9Cthat the SEC is attempt=
ing to exceed its authority under the Advisers Act andengaging in rulemakin=
g by enforcement through its current sweep regarding off-channel communicat=
ions,=E2=80=9D and that Rule 204-2(a)(7) does not cover the sort of intra-d=
esk text messaging that the SEC has been going after at the banks.
Still I basically assume that the SEC will just go down the line extracting=
 flat but lower-than-$125-million fines from all the hedge funds, private e=
quity firms, etc. But maybe not? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Austin Weinstein repo=
rts:

Citadel is preparing to push back against the Securities and Exchange Commi=
ssion=E2=80=99s WhatsApp probe, taking a harder line than the almost two do=
zen banks that have paid hefty settlements over the past two years.
Ken Griffin=E2=80=99s hedge fund has told industry peers that it plans to b=
attle the SEC if the regulator moves against Citadel, according to people f=
amiliar with the talks. And it=E2=80=99s willing to take the agency to cour=
t, said the people, who asked not to be identified discussing private conve=
rsations.
The Miami-based firm would be the first to fight the SEC over any allegatio=
ns of untracked communications. As a hedge fund, it would likely argue that=
 it=E2=80=99s not subject to the same rules as Wall Street banks like JPMor=
gan Chase & Co. and Bank of America Corp., which agreed to pay more than $2=
.5 billion to settle US regulators=E2=80=99 investigations into their emplo=
yees using unofficial messaging platforms for business.

Sure, good for them.

