   =20
      Sculptor
   =20
 =20

The schematic math of the Sculptor Capital Management Inc. situation is:
=09Sculptor is a publicly traded asset manager with about $30 billion of as=
sets under management, roughly half=C2=A0in collateralized loan obligations=
 and the rest in hedge fund and real estate strategies.=09Those $30 billion=
 of client assets pay Sculptor fees of more than $400=C2=A0million per year=
.=09Of those fees, more than $300 million per year goes to Sculptor=E2=80=
=99s employees, with much of it concentrated among the senior people=C2=A0m=
anaging its funds. Its chief executive officer and chief investment officer=
, Jimmy Levin, made $49 million in 2022 and $146 million in 2021.
  [1]

=09A bit less than $0 per year goes to Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders: The=
 firm reported net losses in each of the last two years.=09Being a Sculptor=
 hedge fund manager is quite lucrative, but=C2=A0being a Sculptor sharehold=
er is not particularly.=09This is not a weird anomaly! Being a hedge fund m=
anager is lucrative, and Sculptor is a hedge fund management firm that empl=
oys hedge fund managers. Most hedge fund management firms are privately hel=
d, and roughly all of the money goes to the managers. To compete for talent=
, Sculptor also pays roughly all of its money to its managers. The sharehol=
ders get squeezed. Jimmy Levin did not invent this or anything. Dan Och, Sc=
ulptor=E2=80=99s founder and former CEO/CIO, =E2=80=9Ctook home $3.3 billio=
n since 2007 as Sculptor=E2=80=99s stock price tanked by 96%.=E2=80=9D That=
=E2=80=99s just how it works!=09The result is that Sculptor=E2=80=99s stock=
 price is fairly cheap, since the cash flows to shareholders are a bit less=
 than zero.=09But if you buy=C2=A0all=C2=A0of Sculptor, you can make=C2=A0y=
ourself=C2=A0the CEO, and pay yourself all the fees.

As I  wrote last month:
If you have a public company where most of the cash flows go, not to the sh=
areholders, but to the CEO, then it is cheap to become a shareholder and lu=
crative to become the CEO. But if you buy enough shares you can make yourse=
lf the CEO. There is an arbitrage.
I kind of don=E2=80=99t understand why more hedge fund managers are not bid=
ding to buy Sculptor. But a bunch of them are, in a consortium led by Boaz =
Weinstein, and Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Katherine Burton and Hema Parmar  report=
ed yesterday:

Boaz Weinstein made his name trading in esoteric corners of the credit mark=
ets. But his most audacious bet yet may be trying to catapult his hedge fun=
d firm into the ranks of the industry=E2=80=99s largest players.
To do that, the 50-year-old head of Saba Capital Management is attempting t=
o buy his way to the top. He=E2=80=99s bidding =E2=80=94 with a group of bi=
llionaire pals including Bill Ackman, Marc Lasry and Jeff Yass =E2=80=94 fo=
r Sculptor Capital Management Inc., a beleaguered publicly traded money man=
ager he aims to subsume into his $4 billion firm.
Weinstein=E2=80=99s assets under management could balloon to more than $20 =
billion if he wins Sculptor, requiring only a $700 million investment backe=
d by deep-pocketed friends. While Weinstein=E2=80=99s group made the highes=
t bid, it was rejected for a lower one from Rithm Capital Corp. Sculptor, w=
hich said Rithm=E2=80=99s offer was more certain, won=E2=80=99t let Weinste=
in speak directly to investors or stockholders. =E2=80=A6
Like the chess master he is, Weinstein saw a way to exploit weak competitio=
n and build his empire. Saba=E2=80=99s main fund is slightly niche =E2=80=
=93 short bonds, long volatility =E2=80=94 and while he=E2=80=99s added som=
e other strategies, growing assets is a slow game.
So when Sculptor put itself on the block late last year, Weinstein assemble=
d his all-star team and made a bid. In July, Sculptor picked Rithm =E2=80=
=94 a firm that started out in mortgage servicing rights =E2=80=94 which ag=
reed to pay $11.15 a share, or $639 million. Sculptor rejected Weinstein=E2=
=80=99s higher bid, which now stands at $12.76. =E2=80=A6
Under Weinstein=E2=80=99s plan, Sculptor would be run as its own brand with=
in Saba. With the current CIO in a lesser role, or even gone, Weinstein cou=
ld use the extra money =E2=80=93 Levin was paid $145 million in 2021 =E2=80=
=94 to help retain strategy heads and others among its 100 investment profe=
ssionals.

You do have to pay most of the money to the managers.=C2=A0Burton also  rep=
orted last week:

Boaz Weinstein would offer Sculptor Capital Management Inc. clients the cha=
nce to join his investment in the money manager under the same terms as his=
 billionaire backers, according to people familiar with the plan.
The Saba Capital Management founder and his co-investors view the plan as a=
 sweetener for clients, who must give their approval in order for Weinstein=
=E2=80=99s bid for Sculptor to go through.

It=E2=80=99s an odd sweetener? The reason that Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has=
 given for preferring Rithm is that Rithm would keep Levin, and it thinks t=
hat Sculptor=E2=80=99s clients would prefer to have Levin manage their mone=
y rather than Weinstein. (Since, after all, they are=C2=A0still clients of =
Sculptor, which Levin runs, and they are not currently=C2=A0clients of Saba=
, which Weinstein runs.) We have  talked about this situation a lot; Sculpt=
or=E2=80=99s reasoning strikes me as plausible but weirdly uncertain. (Why =
not ask the clients?) By offering the clients a sweetener, Weinstein is try=
ing to reassure the board that the clients will consent to him taking over.
But why would the clients want to own the firm? I feel like the lesson of S=
culptor is:
=09A well-run hedge fund probably makes money for its clients. (Though Scul=
ptor=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cmain fund has annualized at about 6% since 2018, an=
d its returns more closely track the S&P 500 than other multi-strategy firm=
s,=E2=80=9D report Burton and Parmar.)=09It definitely makes money for its=
=C2=A0managers.=09The=C2=A0shareholders of the management company, not nece=
ssarily?

You have to make money for the clients, you have to pay the investment mana=
gers, and the shareholders just get what=E2=80=99s left over. It makes tota=
l sense for Weinstein to want to=C2=A0buy and run=C2=A0Sculptor; it makes a=
 bit less sense for anyone else to want to=C2=A0help him buy it=C2=A0as an =
outside=C2=A0passive investor. Though I guess Ackman, Lasry and Yass are in=
, which is an endorsement of the idea. Presumably they have to get paid too=
.

