   =20
      Binance
   =20
 =20

Two key=20
questions in crypto regulation are:
=09Will US regulators (and particularly the SEC) remain as hostile to crypt=
o as they are right now, or will the US become more crypto-friendly through=
 some combination of congressional legislation, court rulings that go again=
st the SEC, personnel changes at regulators, etc.?=09If the US=C2=A0does=C2=
=A0remain super hostile to crypto, will that be bad for crypto=C2=A0globall=
y, or will it just mean that crypto becomes a non-US thing? In general, US =
regulators and prosecutors are very=C2=A0good at using the power of the US =
government and the reach of the dollar system to impose US decisions on glo=
bal finance. If you are a   French bank providing financing to a Cuban comp=
any, and the US doesn=E2=80=99t like that, it will stop you. But crypto is =
different! Crypto is anonymous and borderless and irreversible and censorsh=
ip-resistant; if the US decides to ban crypto then it can maybe (maybe) cut=
 US citizens off from the joys of crypto, but it can=E2=80=99t interfere wi=
th crypto=E2=80=99s global growth. Or that is an idea anyway.

This year US   regulators have brought   cases against Binance, the world=
=E2=80=99s biggest crypto exchange. When the SEC sued Binance,   I wrote th=
at Binance=E2=80=99s somewhat cynical attitude=C2=A0to US regulation seemed=
 smart:
Binance noticed that it's illegal to run a crypto exchange in the US, and d=
id it anyway, but minimized and compartmentalized its US exposure: It has r=
elatively few US customers and seems to keep most of its business out of th=
e US.
Well. You can keep your business out of the US, but you can=E2=80=99t keep =
the US out of your business. Today the Wall Street Journal has a report on =
how things are going at Binance. =E2=80=9CThe World=E2=80=99s Biggest Crypt=
o Firm Is Melting Down,=E2=80=9D is the headline:

Under threat of enforcement actions by U.S. agencies, Binance=E2=80=99s emp=
ire is quaking. Over the past three months, more than a dozen senior execut=
ives have left, and the exchange has laid off at least 1,500 employees this=
 year to cut costs and prepare for a decline in business. And while Binance=
 still looms large in crypto, its dominance is dwindling.=C2=A0
Binance now handles about half of all trades where cryptocurrencies are dir=
ectly bought and sold, down from about 70% at the start of the year, accord=
ing to data provider Kaiko. =E2=80=A6
Yi He, Binance=E2=80=99s co-founder and chief marketing officer, vowed to o=
vercome the troubles in a message to Binance staff last month.
=E2=80=9CEvery battle is a do-or-die situation, and the only thing that can=
 defeat us is ourselves,=E2=80=9D she wrote in the message viewed by the Jo=
urnal. =E2=80=9CWe have won countless times, and we need to win this time a=
s well.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CYou just can=E2=80=99t quantify what would happen to the industry =
if Binance disappeared, given it has been responsible for fostering a huge =
amount of innovation and growth,=E2=80=9D said Anthony Georgiades, a genera=
l partner at Innovating Capital, a fund that invests in early-growth compan=
ies. =E2=80=A6
Pressure from the DOJ was partly responsible for [Binance co-founder Changp=
eng] Zhao=E2=80=99s decision to begin winding down Binance=E2=80=99s busine=
ss in Russia, once one of its most important markets, the person said. Over=
 the following two weeks, Binance barred customers from using the sanctione=
d banks and forced out the executives managing its Russia business. It said=
 it was considering a full withdrawal from Russia.

Can US regulators ban crypto trading in Russia? No? But, also, kind of?

